{"author":{"id":"138b13306404778af60b1d60d606624fec41556ddac480b2d5f762806ce84fed"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1782958607,"nonce":"cUmcv7N3+/NH/YaWzqdAdM1b91E=","kind":"plans","title":"kref `ls` output + entry reattribution — Implementation Plan","content_type":"text/markdown"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1782958607,"nonce":"xi2R2w/BebO/5hYtn8WxD0JqESw=","body":"# kref `ls` output + entry reattribution — Implementation Plan\n\n\u003e **For agentic workers:** REQUIRED SUB-SKILL: Use superpowers:subagent-driven-development (recommended) or superpowers:executing-plans to implement this plan task-by-task. Steps use checkbox (`- [ ]`) syntax for tracking.\n\n**Goal:** Add a shell-friendly `kref ls` output (`--plain`) with selectable columns (`--columns`/`--wide`), and entry reattribution (`kref update --reset-author`/`--author`).\n\n**Architecture:** Two independent slices. (A) A new append-only `Reattribute` op overwrites the displayed author; `Store.Reattribute` and two `update` flags drive it. (B) `internal/render` gains a column-driven renderer feeding both the existing aligned table and a new TSV plain mode; `list` gains the three presentation flags. Render stays pure (no TTY/JSON logic).\n\n**Tech Stack:** Go, git-bug `entity/dag`, Ginkgo v2 + Gomega. Build/test via `task` with `GOTOOLCHAIN=auto`; `./bin/kref` for manual runs (sibling `bin/gitleaks` auto-resolved).\n\n**Conventions:** Run tests with `task test MODE=llm` (errors-only) or scope a package with `GOTOOLCHAIN=auto KREF_GITLEAKS=$PWD/bin/gitleaks go test ./internal/entry/ -run TestEntry`. The `entry` suite entry point is `TestEntry`, `store` is `TestStore`, `render` is `TestRender`, `cmd/kref` is `TestCLI`. The `entry` package's specs are black-box `package entry_test`.\n\n---\n\n## Slice A — Reattribution\n\n### Task 1: `Reattribute` operation (entry package)\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `internal/entry/operations.go` (add op const, struct, constructor, methods, unmarshaler case)\n- Test: `internal/entry/operations_test.go` (or the existing entry spec file — match where sibling op specs live)\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Write the failing test**\n\nAdd to the entry specs (black-box `package entry_test`; mirror how existing op specs build an identity — reuse the suite's helper for making an `identity.Interface`, e.g. the same constructor other op specs use):\n\n```go\nvar _ = Describe(\"Reattribute\", func() {\n    It(\"overwrites the snapshot author with its payload, not the op author\", func() {\n        opAuthor := makeIdentity(\"Op Runner\", \"runner@example.com\") // existing test helper\n        e := entry.NewEntry()\n        e.Append(entry.NewCreate(opAuthor, \"spec\", \"Title\"))\n        e.Append(entry.NewReattribute(opAuthor, \"New Owner\", \"owner@example.com\"))\n        s := e.Compile()\n        Expect(s.CreatedBy).To(Equal(\"New Owner\"))\n        Expect(s.CreatedByEmail).To(Equal(\"owner@example.com\"))\n    })\n\n    It(\"rejects an empty name or email\", func() {\n        a := makeIdentity(\"X\", \"x@example.com\")\n        Expect(entry.NewReattribute(a, \"\", \"e@x.com\").Validate()).To(HaveOccurred())\n        Expect(entry.NewReattribute(a, \"Name\", \"\").Validate()).To(HaveOccurred())\n    })\n})\n```\n\n\u003e If the entry suite has no `makeIdentity`/`NewEntry` helper, check the existing op specs for the exact constructors they use (e.g. `entry.New()` or a test identity builder) and copy that idiom — do not invent a new helper.\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Run test to verify it fails**\n\nRun: `GOTOOLCHAIN=auto KREF_GITLEAKS=$PWD/bin/gitleaks go test ./internal/entry/ -run TestEntry`\nExpected: FAIL — `entry.NewReattribute` undefined.\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Add the op const**\n\nIn `internal/entry/operations.go`, add `ReattributeOp` to the `const ( _ dag.OperationType = iota … )` block, **after** `UntrackOp` (appending keeps existing op-type integer values stable, which matters for already-stored ops):\n\n```go\n\tTrackOp\n\tUntrackOp\n\tReattributeOp\n)\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Add the struct, constructor, and methods**\n\nAdd near the other ops (mirror `SetTitle`/`SetKind`):\n\n```go\n// Reattribute overwrites the displayed author of an entry. The op is authored\n// by whoever runs it (its OpBase author), while its payload carries the new\n// display author — so history records who reattributed without rewriting the\n// immutable Create op.\ntype Reattribute struct {\n\tdag.OpBase\n\tName  string `json:\"name\"`\n\tEmail string `json:\"email\"`\n}\n\nfunc NewReattribute(author identity.Interface, name, email string) *Reattribute {\n\treturn \u0026Reattribute{\n\t\tOpBase: dag.NewOpBase(ReattributeOp, author, time.Now().Unix()),\n\t\tName:   name,\n\t\tEmail:  email,\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc (op *Reattribute) Id() entity.Id { return dag.IdOperation(op, \u0026op.OpBase) }\n\nfunc (op *Reattribute) Validate() error {\n\tif op.Name == \"\" {\n\t\treturn fmt.Errorf(\"author name required\")\n\t}\n\tif op.Email == \"\" {\n\t\treturn fmt.Errorf(\"author email required\")\n\t}\n\treturn op.OpBase.Validate(op, ReattributeOp)\n}\n\nfunc (op *Reattribute) Apply(s *Snapshot) {\n\ts.CreatedBy = op.Name\n\ts.CreatedByEmail = op.Email\n\ts.UpdatedAt = op.Time()\n}\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Register in the unmarshaler**\n\nIn `operationUnmarshaler`, add a case alongside the others:\n\n```go\n\tcase ReattributeOp:\n\t\top = \u0026Reattribute{}\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 6: Run test to verify it passes**\n\nRun: `GOTOOLCHAIN=auto KREF_GITLEAKS=$PWD/bin/gitleaks go test ./internal/entry/ -run TestEntry`\nExpected: PASS.\n\n- [ ] **Step 7: Add the log mapping**\n\nIn `internal/entry/history.go`, add a case to `Entry.Log()`'s type switch so reattribution shows in `kref log`:\n\n```go\n\t\tcase *Reattribute:\n\t\t\tle.Op, le.Detail = \"reattribute\", o.Name+\" \u003c\"+o.Email+\"\u003e\"\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 8: Run the whole entry suite**\n\nRun: `GOTOOLCHAIN=auto KREF_GITLEAKS=$PWD/bin/gitleaks go test ./internal/entry/ -run TestEntry`\nExpected: PASS (no regressions).\n\n- [ ] **Step 9: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add internal/entry/operations.go internal/entry/history.go internal/entry/operations_test.go\ngit commit -m \"feat(entry): add Reattribute op for changing displayed author\"\n```\n\n---\n\n### Task 2: `Store.Reattribute`\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `internal/store/store.go` (add method after `SetKind`)\n- Test: `internal/store/store_test.go` (match the package's existing store-spec file)\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Write the failing test**\n\nMirror existing store specs (white-box `package store`; reuse the suite's helper that inits a temp store — find it in the existing store spec setup):\n\n```go\nvar _ = Describe(\"Reattribute\", func() {\n    It(\"changes the entry's displayed author\", func() {\n        s := newTestStore() // existing helper: inits a temp repo + identity\n        id, err := s.Add(\"spec\", \"Title\", \"body\", entry.TierPersonal)\n        Expect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred())\n\n        Expect(s.Reattribute(id, \"New Owner\", \"owner@example.com\")).To(Succeed())\n\n        snap, err := s.Get(id)\n        Expect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred())\n        Expect(snap.CreatedBy).To(Equal(\"New Owner\"))\n        Expect(snap.CreatedByEmail).To(Equal(\"owner@example.com\"))\n    })\n\n    It(\"errors on a missing entry\", func() {\n        s := newTestStore()\n        Expect(s.Reattribute(\"deadbeef\", \"N\", \"e@x.com\")).NotTo(Succeed())\n    })\n})\n```\n\n\u003e Confirm the exact signature of `Store.Add` and the temp-store helper name from the existing store specs before writing — copy their idiom rather than guessing argument order.\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Run test to verify it fails**\n\nRun: `GOTOOLCHAIN=auto KREF_GITLEAKS=$PWD/bin/gitleaks go test ./internal/store/ -run TestStore`\nExpected: FAIL — `s.Reattribute` undefined.\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Implement the method**\n\nIn `internal/store/store.go`, copy the `SetKind` shape exactly, swapping the op:\n\n```go\n// Reattribute appends a displayed-author change to an entry, searching all tiers.\nfunc (s *Store) Reattribute(id entity.Id, name, email string) error {\n\tfor _, t := range entry.AllTiers() {\n\t\te, err := entry.Read(s.repo, t, id)\n\t\tif err != nil {\n\t\t\tif entity.IsErrNotFound(err) {\n\t\t\t\tcontinue\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t\treturn fmt.Errorf(\"read %s in tier %s: %w\", id, t, err)\n\t\t}\n\t\te.Append(entry.NewReattribute(s.author, name, email))\n\t\treturn e.Commit(s.repo)\n\t}\n\treturn fmt.Errorf(\"entry %s not found\", id)\n}\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Run test to verify it passes**\n\nRun: `GOTOOLCHAIN=auto KREF_GITLEAKS=$PWD/bin/gitleaks go test ./internal/store/ -run TestStore`\nExpected: PASS.\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add internal/store/store.go internal/store/store_test.go\ngit commit -m \"feat(store): add Reattribute to change an entry's displayed author\"\n```\n\n---\n\n### Task 3: `kref update --reset-author` / `--author`\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `cmd/kref/commands.go` (`newUpdateCmd`: flags, validation, author parsing, guard relaxation, call)\n- Test: `cmd/kref/cli_test.go` (add specs near the existing update specs; helpers `run`/`runIn` exist)\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Write the failing tests**\n\n```go\nvar _ = Describe(\"update reattribution\", func() {\n    It(\"--reset-author sets the entry author to the current identity\", func() {\n        // create under an explicit actor, then reset to the init identity\n        out := run(\"add\", \"--kind\", \"spec\", \"--title\", \"T\", \"--body\", \"b\")\n        id := extractID(out) // existing helper used by other cli specs\n        run(\"update\", id, \"--author\", \"Old One \u003cold@example.com\u003e\")\n        run(\"update\", id, \"--reset-author\")\n        show := run(\"show\", id)\n        Expect(show).To(ContainSubstring(\"LLM (riotbox)\")) // the init identity (see suite setup)\n        Expect(show).NotTo(ContainSubstring(\"old@example.com\"))\n    })\n\n    It(\"--author sets an explicit author\", func() {\n        id := extractID(run(\"add\", \"--kind\", \"spec\", \"--title\", \"T\", \"--body\", \"b\"))\n        run(\"update\", id, \"--author\", \"Jane Roe \u003cjane@example.com\u003e\")\n        Expect(run(\"show\", id)).To(ContainSubstring(\"Jane Roe \u003cjane@example.com\u003e\"))\n    })\n\n    It(\"rejects --reset-author with --author together\", func() {\n        id := extractID(run(\"add\", \"--kind\", \"spec\", \"--title\", \"T\", \"--body\", \"b\"))\n        Expect(runErr(\"update\", id, \"--reset-author\", \"--author\", \"A \u003ca@x.com\u003e\")).To(HaveOccurred())\n    })\n\n    It(\"rejects a malformed --author\", func() {\n        id := extractID(run(\"add\", \"--kind\", \"spec\", \"--title\", \"T\", \"--body\", \"b\"))\n        Expect(runErr(\"update\", id, \"--author\", \"no-email-here\")).To(HaveOccurred())\n    })\n})\n```\n\n\u003e `run` asserts success and returns output; for the error cases use the suite's existing error-returning helper. If none exists, add a minimal `runErr(args...) error` next to `run` in `cli_test.go` that executes the root cmd and returns `cmd.Execute()`’s error (do NOT assert success). Confirm the actual init identity string from the suite bootstrap and the `extractID` helper name before finalizing.\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Run tests to verify they fail**\n\nRun: `GOTOOLCHAIN=auto KREF_GITLEAKS=$PWD/bin/gitleaks go test ./cmd/kref/ -run TestCLI`\nExpected: FAIL — unknown flags `--reset-author`/`--author`.\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Add an author parser**\n\nIn `cmd/kref/commands.go` (near `newUpdateCmd`), add a helper that parses `\"Name \u003cemail\u003e\"`:\n\n```go\n// parseAuthor splits a \"Name \u003cemail\u003e\" string into its parts, erroring if the\n// shape is wrong or either part is empty.\nfunc parseAuthor(s string) (name, email string, err error) {\n\topen := strings.LastIndex(s, \"\u003c\")\n\tclose := strings.LastIndex(s, \"\u003e\")\n\tif open \u003c 0 || close \u003c open || close != len(strings.TrimSpace(s))-1 {\n\t\treturn \"\", \"\", fmt.Errorf(\"author must be in the form \\\"Name \u003cemail\u003e\\\": %q\", s)\n\t}\n\tname = strings.TrimSpace(s[:open])\n\temail = strings.TrimSpace(s[open+1 : close])\n\tif name == \"\" || email == \"\" {\n\t\treturn \"\", \"\", fmt.Errorf(\"author must be in the form \\\"Name \u003cemail\u003e\\\": %q\", s)\n\t}\n\treturn name, email, nil\n}\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Wire the flags and behavior**\n\nIn `newUpdateCmd`, declare flags alongside the existing ones:\n\n```go\n\tvar resetAuthor bool\n\tvar author string\n```\n\nRegister at the bottom with the other `c.Flags()` calls:\n\n```go\n\tc.Flags().BoolVar(\u0026resetAuthor, \"reset-author\", false, \"reattribute the entry to your current kref identity\")\n\tc.Flags().StringVar(\u0026author, \"author\", \"\", \"reattribute the entry to an explicit author, \\\"Name \u003cemail\u003e\\\"\")\n```\n\nIn `RunE`, after the existing `bodyChanged/fileSet/titleSet/kindSet` setup, add:\n\n```go\n\t\tauthorSet := cmd.Flags().Changed(\"author\")\n\t\tif resetAuthor \u0026\u0026 authorSet {\n\t\t\treturn fmt.Errorf(\"use one of --reset-author or --author, not both\")\n\t\t}\n\t\treattributing := resetAuthor || authorSet\n```\n\nRelax the \"nothing to update\" guard so reattribution alone is valid — change:\n\n```go\n\t\tif !haveBody \u0026\u0026 !titleSet \u0026\u0026 !kindSet {\n\t\t\treturn fmt.Errorf(\"nothing to update (give --body/--file, --title, --kind, or pipe a body on stdin)\")\n\t\t}\n```\n\nto:\n\n```go\n\t\tif !haveBody \u0026\u0026 !titleSet \u0026\u0026 !kindSet \u0026\u0026 !reattributing {\n\t\t\treturn fmt.Errorf(\"nothing to update (give --body/--file, --title, --kind, --reset-author, --author, or pipe a body on stdin)\")\n\t\t}\n```\n\n\u003e **stdin guard:** the current `default:` branch of the body `switch` reads stdin whenever neither `--body` nor `--file` is set. With reattribution-only invocations there is no piped body, and a TTY read would hang. Guard it: change the `switch` so the `default` (stdin) branch is skipped when `reattributing \u0026\u0026 !bodyChanged \u0026\u0026 !fileSet \u0026\u0026 !titleSet \u0026\u0026 !kindSet`. Concretely, wrap the stdin read:\n\u003e ```go\n\u003e \t\tdefault:\n\u003e \t\t\tif reattributing \u0026\u0026 !titleSet \u0026\u0026 !kindSet {\n\u003e \t\t\t\tbreak // reattribution-only: no body on stdin\n\u003e \t\t\t}\n\u003e \t\t\traw, err := io.ReadAll(cmd.InOrStdin())\n\u003e \t\t\t...\n\u003e ```\n\nAfter the existing body/title/kind application block and **before** the final `s.Get(id)`, apply reattribution:\n\n```go\n\t\tif reattributing {\n\t\t\tname, email := s.Author()\n\t\t\tif authorSet {\n\t\t\t\tif name, email, err = parseAuthor(author); err != nil {\n\t\t\t\t\treturn err\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t\tif err := s.Reattribute(id, name, email); err != nil {\n\t\t\t\treturn err\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t}\n```\n\n\u003e `s.Author()` returns `(name, email string)` — confirmed in `internal/store/store.go`.\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Run tests to verify they pass**\n\nRun: `GOTOOLCHAIN=auto KREF_GITLEAKS=$PWD/bin/gitleaks go test ./cmd/kref/ -run TestCLI`\nExpected: PASS.\n\n- [ ] **Step 6: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add cmd/kref/commands.go cmd/kref/cli_test.go\ngit commit -m \"feat(update): reattribute entries via --reset-author and --author\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Slice B — `ls` columns + plain output\n\n### Task 4: Column-driven renderer (render package)\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `internal/render/render.go` (column model + `RenderList`; refactor `List` to delegate)\n- Test: `internal/render/render_test.go` (existing default-table specs must keep passing)\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Write the failing tests**\n\nAdd to `render_test.go` (white-box `package render`; build snapshots directly as the existing specs do):\n\n```go\nvar _ = Describe(\"RenderList columns + plain\", func() {\n    items := []*entry.Snapshot{\n        {ID: \"aaaaaaaaaaaa1111\", Kind: \"spec\", Status: \"open\", Tier: string(entry.TierShared),\n            Title: \"Alpha\", CreatedBy: \"Jane Roe\", CreatedByEmail: \"jane@x.com\",\n            UpdatedAt: time.Date(2026, 6, 27, 0, 0, 0, 0, time.UTC)},\n    }\n\n    It(\"ParseColumns rejects an unknown token\", func() {\n        _, err := render.ParseColumns(\"id,bogus,title\")\n        Expect(err).To(MatchError(ContainSubstring(\"bogus\")))\n    })\n\n    It(\"plain mode is TSV with no header/footer/color and a bare tier word\", func() {\n        var b bytes.Buffer\n        cols, _ := render.ParseColumns(\"tier,id,author\")\n        render.RenderList(\u0026b, items, render.ListOptions{Columns: cols, Plain: true})\n        Expect(b.String()).To(Equal(\"shared\\taaaaaaaaaaaa\\tJane Roe\\n\"))\n    })\n\n    It(\"table mode prints headers for selected columns\", func() {\n        var b bytes.Buffer\n        cols, _ := render.ParseColumns(\"id,author,updated,title\")\n        render.RenderList(\u0026b, items, render.ListOptions{Columns: cols})\n        out := b.String()\n        Expect(out).To(ContainSubstring(\"ID\"))\n        Expect(out).To(ContainSubstring(\"AUTHOR\"))\n        Expect(out).To(ContainSubstring(\"UPDATED\"))\n        Expect(out).To(ContainSubstring(\"Jane Roe\"))\n        Expect(out).To(ContainSubstring(\"2026-06-27\"))\n    })\n\n    It(\"WideColumns includes author and updated\", func() {\n        Expect(render.WideColumns).To(ContainElement(render.ColAuthor))\n        Expect(render.WideColumns).To(ContainElement(render.ColUpdated))\n    })\n})\n\n// These guard tests fail loudly if internals drift: a renamed Snapshot field, a\n// new Column without a header/cell mapping, or a cell wired to the wrong field.\nvar _ = Describe(\"RenderList column registry consistency\", func() {\n    // A snapshot whose every field carries a unique sentinel, so a cell wired to\n    // the wrong field produces a detectably wrong value.\n    sentinel := \u0026entry.Snapshot{\n        ID:             \"0123456789abcdef0000\", // ShortID -\u003e \"0123456789ab\"\n        Kind:           \"KIND_SENT\",\n        Status:         \"STATUS_SENT\",\n        Tier:           string(entry.TierShared),\n        Title:          \"TITLE_SENT\",\n        Labels:         []string{\"l1\", \"l2\"},\n        Tracked:        true,\n        TrackedPath:    \"PATH_SENT\",\n        CreatedBy:      \"AUTHOR_SENT\",\n        CreatedByEmail: \"EMAIL_SENT\",\n        CreatedAt:      time.Date(2026, 1, 2, 0, 0, 0, 0, time.UTC),\n        UpdatedAt:      time.Date(2026, 3, 4, 0, 0, 0, 0, time.UTC),\n    }\n    // Expected plain-cell value per column. This map MUST list every column in\n    // render.AllColumns — the test below asserts exact coverage, so adding a\n    // Column without updating this map fails the suite.\n    expected := map[render.Column]string{\n        render.ColTier:    \"shared\",\n        render.ColID:      \"0123456789ab\",\n        render.ColFullID:  \"0123456789abcdef0000\",\n        render.ColKind:    \"KIND_SENT\",\n        render.ColStatus:  \"STATUS_SENT\",\n        render.ColTitle:   \"TITLE_SENT\",\n        render.ColAuthor:  \"AUTHOR_SENT\",\n        render.ColEmail:   \"EMAIL_SENT\",\n        render.ColCreated: \"2026-01-02\",\n        render.ColUpdated: \"2026-03-04\",\n        render.ColLabels:  \"l1, l2\",\n        render.ColTracked: \"yes\",\n        render.ColPath:    \"PATH_SENT\",\n    }\n\n    It(\"every column in AllColumns parses and has a header\", func() {\n        for _, c := range render.AllColumns {\n            cols, err := render.ParseColumns(string(c))\n            Expect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred(), \"column %q must parse\", c)\n            Expect(cols).To(Equal([]render.Column{c}))\n            Expect(render.HeaderFor(c)).NotTo(BeEmpty(), \"column %q must have a header\", c)\n        }\n    })\n\n    It(\"the expected-cell map covers exactly AllColumns (no missing, no orphans)\", func() {\n        Expect(expected).To(HaveLen(len(render.AllColumns)))\n        for _, c := range render.AllColumns {\n            _, ok := expected[c]\n            Expect(ok).To(BeTrue(), \"column %q missing from the expected-cell map\", c)\n        }\n    })\n\n    It(\"each column renders its own field (catches field-swap regressions)\", func() {\n        for _, c := range render.AllColumns {\n            var b bytes.Buffer\n            render.RenderList(\u0026b, []*entry.Snapshot{sentinel}, render.ListOptions{\n                Columns: []render.Column{c}, Plain: true,\n            })\n            Expect(strings.TrimRight(b.String(), \"\\n\")).To(Equal(expected[c]),\n                \"plain cell for column %q rendered the wrong field\", c)\n        }\n    })\n\n    It(\"DefaultColumns and WideColumns contain only valid columns\", func() {\n        valid := map[render.Column]bool{}\n        for _, c := range render.AllColumns {\n            valid[c] = true\n        }\n        for _, c := range append(append([]render.Column{}, render.DefaultColumns...), render.WideColumns...) {\n            Expect(valid[c]).To(BeTrue(), \"preset references unknown column %q\", c)\n        }\n    })\n})\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Run tests to verify they fail**\n\nRun: `GOTOOLCHAIN=auto KREF_GITLEAKS=$PWD/bin/gitleaks go test ./internal/render/ -run TestRender`\nExpected: FAIL — `render.ParseColumns`/`RenderList`/`ListOptions`/`ColAuthor`/`WideColumns` undefined.\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Add the column model**\n\nIn `internal/render/render.go`:\n\n```go\n// Column is a selectable list column.\ntype Column string\n\nconst (\n\tColTier    Column = \"tier\"\n\tColID      Column = \"id\"\n\tColFullID  Column = \"fullid\"\n\tColKind    Column = \"kind\"\n\tColStatus  Column = \"status\"\n\tColTitle   Column = \"title\"\n\tColAuthor  Column = \"author\"\n\tColEmail   Column = \"email\"\n\tColCreated Column = \"created\"\n\tColUpdated Column = \"updated\"\n\tColLabels  Column = \"labels\"\n\tColTracked Column = \"tracked\"\n\tColPath    Column = \"path\"\n)\n\n// AllColumns is the canonical, ordered registry of every column. It is the\n// single source of truth: ParseColumns, the header lookup, and the cell\n// switches are all checked against it by the registry-consistency specs, so a\n// new column that misses a header or a cell mapping fails the suite.\nvar AllColumns = []Column{\n\tColTier, ColID, ColFullID, ColKind, ColStatus, ColTitle,\n\tColAuthor, ColEmail, ColCreated, ColUpdated, ColLabels, ColTracked, ColPath,\n}\n\n// DefaultColumns is today's table; WideColumns adds author + updated.\nvar DefaultColumns = []Column{ColTier, ColID, ColKind, ColStatus, ColTitle}\nvar WideColumns = []Column{ColTier, ColID, ColKind, ColStatus, ColAuthor, ColUpdated, ColTitle}\n\nvar columnHeaders = map[Column]string{\n\tColTier: \"TIER\", ColID: \"ID\", ColFullID: \"ID\", ColKind: \"KIND\", ColStatus: \"STATUS\",\n\tColTitle: \"TITLE\", ColAuthor: \"AUTHOR\", ColEmail: \"EMAIL\", ColCreated: \"CREATED\",\n\tColUpdated: \"UPDATED\", ColLabels: \"LABELS\", ColTracked: \"TRACKED\", ColPath: \"PATH\",\n}\n\n// HeaderFor returns the column header label (exported for the consistency specs).\nfunc HeaderFor(c Column) string { return columnHeaders[c] }\n\nfunc validColumns() string {\n\tnames := make([]string, len(AllColumns))\n\tfor i, c := range AllColumns {\n\t\tnames[i] = string(c)\n\t}\n\treturn strings.Join(names, \" \")\n}\n\n// ParseColumns turns \"a,b,c\" into ordered columns, erroring on unknown tokens.\nfunc ParseColumns(s string) ([]Column, error) {\n\tparts := strings.Split(s, \",\")\n\tcols := make([]Column, 0, len(parts))\n\tfor _, p := range parts {\n\t\tc := Column(strings.TrimSpace(p))\n\t\tif _, ok := columnHeaders[c]; !ok {\n\t\t\treturn nil, fmt.Errorf(\"unknown column %q (valid: %s)\", p, validColumns())\n\t\t}\n\t\tcols = append(cols, c)\n\t}\n\treturn cols, nil\n}\n\n// ListOptions configures RenderList. Columns defaults to DefaultColumns when nil.\ntype ListOptions struct {\n\tColumns []Column\n\tPlain   bool\n\tColor   bool\n\tShowAll bool\n}\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Add the cell helpers**\n\n```go\n// tableCell is the uncolored table cell (gly